{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17566707","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17566707"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:47:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:47:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18872"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18872","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18872"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.5,0.24,0.08,0.1,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11605"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79908"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11605","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11605"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18872"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65204"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2550"},{"type":"tags","id":"3949"},{"type":"tags","id":"3955"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27313"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79908","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79908"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old man is brought into the Emergency Department resuscitation bay following a motorbike accident. Following immediate resuscitation measures and stabilisation it is rapidly ascertained that he has sustained a spinal cord injury. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENeurological examination reveals quadriplegia. Bedside tests show preserved diaphragmatic function and inspiratory volume, but poor expiratory pressure and a weak cough reflex.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the highest level at which his spinal cord could be injured?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["C6","C4","C3","T1","C7"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case demonstrates the importance of understanding spinal cord innervation of respiratory muscles. The key finding is the preservation of diaphragmatic function with impaired expiratory muscles.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EC6\u003C/strong\u003E represents the highest possible level of injury that would produce this pattern of respiratory muscle dysfunction. At this level, the phrenic nerve (C3-C5) remains intact, preserving diaphragmatic function, while interrupting innervation to the intercostal and abdominal muscles needed for forced expiration and cough.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn injury at \u003Cstrong\u003EC3\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003EC4\u003C/strong\u003E would affect the phrenic nerve, resulting in diaphragmatic paralysis, which is not present in this case. These patients typically require mechanical ventilation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInjuries at \u003Cstrong\u003EC7\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003ET1\u003C/strong\u003E would be too low to explain the severity of respiratory compromise seen in this patient, as some intercostal muscle function would be preserved.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe diaphragm provides approximately 65% of vital capacity during normal breathing. However, forced expiration and cough require the coordinated action of intercostal and abdominal muscles. Loss of these muscles results in ineffective clearance of secretions and increased risk of respiratory complications.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The phrenic nerve (C3-C5) innervates the diaphragm, the primary muscle of inspiration.","Intercostal and abdominal muscles (T1-T11) are essential for forced expiration and cough.","A spinal cord injury at C6 preserves diaphragmatic function while impairing intercostal and abdominal muscle function."],"references":["Berlowitz DJ, Wadsworth B, Ross J. Respiratory problems and management in people with spinal cord injury. Breathe (Sheff). 2016 Dec;12(4):328-340. doi: 10.1183/20734735.012616. PMID: 28270863; PMCID: PMC5335574."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65204"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18872"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65204","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65204"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-16T11:15:26+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-16T11:16:07+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11605"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79908"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"